segments.text: I was mentioning I was very interested in the trivia of A&M, especially as it relates to sports.

And I've done a number of speeches that, depending on how long you want, 15 to 30 minutes, even going with the traveling Aggies to Ireland last year, I'd have campusology questions because everybody can identify with them.
But I might ask, what is A&M's greatest football game?
When the course center, I have to give a lot of tours.
And I'd get down to the end where one of the cases where we have one half of it, two of the panels devoted to General Rutter.
On the other side, two to Dr. Sanders, who the Core Center is named after because he gave us the $1.5 million gift.
But I would ask the question, if I happen to be in that part of the Core Center, or even at reunions or whatever, what was A&M's greatest football game?
And it'll come around after a while.
Someone will say the Center College game.
And you ask the question about that game, you can say, well, why is that game so important?
And you can go back and there's an entire epistle could be written about that game.
The coach for Center College,
He had been fired at A&M, had a tremendous winning record, had been fired, and here he is now coaching a center college, a little school up in Kentucky.
and of course where the debates took place, the second one this year for the president race, he turned down the Rose Bowl.
They had beaten Harvard the game before, but why did he want to come to Texas A&M and play?
Was it revenge?
When I say A&M, it was actually the start of the Cotton Bowl Classic called the Dixie Classic.
They played in Dallas, but why would he want to come there instead of going to Rose Bowl?
I sometimes think, well, Charlie Moran had 11 football players on that team from Fort Worth, Dallas, so maybe the recruiting was good there.
Who knows?
Very interesting game.
Bo McMillan was their quarterback, top football player in America that year, later coached at Kansas.
But Bo McMillan would have won the Heisman if they had won it.
I like to think he made two mistakes that day.
Right before the kickoff, he got married on the 50-yard line.
And so he said, I do.
The second thing he said was kick to that little guy in the corner.
And the kickoff, Dr. Sanders, who the core center is named after, Little Sammy, ran the kickoff back 55 yards.
And so they didn't kick to Little Sammy anymore.
But you go with that game, and you say, what is it famous for?
It's famous for the 12th man.
And if you...
Want to spin off of that, you can say, well, why was it famous, you know, the 12th man?
And they'll say, well, of course, the 12th man never played football.
He ran track, played basketball.
I think 99.9% of people will tell you that.
But if you research a little bit, you'll find that, yes, he did play against Texas the next year.
He caught a 25-yard pass for a touchdown.
And the score was tied 7 to 7 inside the last minute.
He took another 25 to the 4.
A&M scored and won 14 to 7, 19-22 against Texas.
The Dixie Classic, of course, was January 2, 1922.
So the next football season, you got a little bit of insight into the 12th man being an all-around football player.
I'd mentioned earlier, we'll get back on Charlie Moran, he had umpired in either two or three World Series also, was an outstanding coach, but...
I like to ask the question now after all of that garbage is why did A&M win?
And you'll get everything from they had to fight in Texas Aggie spirit to whatever.
I like to point and say right there at that case with the banner in it and with the pennant in it, I say I like to think A&M won that day because Center College came out wearing orange and white.

and so those are the kind of things that you could you know you could you could throw in but but uh back uh back uh in my days again i remember uh my freshman year very very well uh we had we went out to the clay pits we were playing baylor and waco our unit didn't go to the game it was not a court trip but we were expected to go i can remember that
Probably one of the greatest games A&M's ever played.
I think we scored four times in the last 15 and a half minutes to come back and beat Baylor.
We were down two touchdowns.
It was one of those unbelievable games, and we listened to it on the radio out there, and I think we had a beer bus.
Of course, it wasn't supposed to be drinking, but at all the parties there was alcohol, basically.
Where were the clay pits?
Out across Welborn Road.
How far?
I guess, if I want to remember right, it's probably seven miles or so.
And then west?
Mm-hmm.
down in somebody's pasture.
Was there supposed to be permission?
I don't know.
Of course, being a freshman, you never knew.
And the only time I ever went was that freshman year of the Baylor game.
I can remember Tuesday night yell practice.
Some of the yellators were very upset that some of the units didn't go, and they knew that our unit actually went to
the clay pits, and so we were singled out even with over 4,000 freshmen in the corps.
Our outfit got singled out that we didn't go to game.
And so we were... Now, when people went to the clay pits, were there any women along ever?
Not the, that was the only time I went.
Now, I've seen pictures
I've been through thousands of pictures in the course center and I've seen pictures of gals there.
But usually it was all male, wasn't it?
Oh, yeah.
And did you skinny dip or did you wear a bathing suit?
We always wore a bathing suit.
Who brought the beer?
I don't remember.
I just remember it was always there, you know.
Of course, as only going to it one time.
Now, we had a lot of parties we would have through my junior and senior year, especially.
We had a lot of parties with sororities or things.
One of the best guys, it seemed like, at ranging parties was Dr. Gary Halter.
He always seemed to have a connection.
He was a year behind me.
We used to hitchhike home together some.
He was from Wichita Falls.
But somebody would set up a party with a sorority, maybe, or even a dorm at Sam Houston or Texas, and two stories I can throw in right fast.
We always had a court trip either to Fort Worth or to Dallas.
And I can remember going to my post office box and, dear Box 5611, I'm Box 5611.
My name is Yolanda .
My wife says I never forget anything, but she could never understand why I couldn't remember anything when I was a freshman or in school.
But I remember that a lot of guys
what you consider a blind date based on their box mate at Tessie.
Did this Tessie ask you for a date?
No, but she was very friendly.
But as I remember, I told you I was SHY with the capital SHY.
So you didn't receive it.
All I remember is Yolanda Mayhouse.
But by the time I came a junior, we would have parties and blind dates.
And I remember one that Gary was responsible for setting up over at Austin with somebody he knew.
Pretty sure Gary did this one.
And it was with a sorority, and I was a junior, and my roommate and I decided that we were going to make a lot of money, so we sold setups.
We sold cokes and ice, and we probably made $70, $80 that night.
We were in king cotton, but we had a fish dunkin'.
Eddie Duncan had a blind date with a high school senior who was visiting, someone named...
Linda Bird Johnson.
And I can remember the Monday mornings, the only time I've ever heard a freshman, as we would say in the Corps, fart off or make fun of another freshman.
That morning, the whistle jock blew the whistle and said,
Fish Duncan went all the way with LBJ.
And, of course, that was that slogan the same year that we were at the Baylor football game in Waco.
And that was the Baylor game my freshman year we didn't go to.
But junior year, I remember an airplane flew over dropping out leaflets.
And it's when Lyndon Johnson was running for vice president and senator.
And it said on the outside, don't be half safe.
And then you opened it up and it said, strike LBJ twice.
But those kind of things.
But we did have a lot of parties and dates.
A lot of guys, the dances were always big.
I don't think in the time I was at A&M I ever had a date for a dance down here.

You know, first place, it cost a little bit of money, and you'd have dates out of town or go home with somebody, but having somebody come in here and pay all of that, but I think the majority of the people did, though.
As far as you remember, how were women treated at A&M social events?
I'll give you an example.
G. Raleigh White, I missed one basketball game in five years, even though I told you I worked the intramurals four years.

I can remember if a girl was there, especially walking up those stairs, how the animals would all, certain girls, you know, and they would have to come, if they came to our dorm, there was not the lounges that were there when I came back to teach ROTC in the 70s between the dorms.
They'd have to sit out there on the cement block or stairs, I mean steps out there.

you could call it a bench but it'd be a funny name for it but uh uh then the cat calls the names uh but now after that at the the senior ball oh yes they uh they were treated like royalty yeah they oh definitely definitely because most of the time there was girls that were coming from off campus and and also uh girls uh uh it was kind of unwritten
ruled that a lot of girls didn't date, didn't date, local girls didn't date Aggies, or Allen Academy.
At that time, I know I did go out some with one of the, in fact, he was my psychology prof.
I went out with his daughter some, and I roomed with a guy my,
and part of my senior year until I went to staff the third week.
I was always dating local girls, but it was kind of a, and most of the girls that would come in here were ones that they had dated from their home or high school or whatever.
Describe being a freshman on a court trip.
The first thing I remember is somehow I got to the Rice game.
And I remember that we stayed at the Rice Hotel, and I think there were 14 of us that stayed in the room that night.
And I remember we did not, my freshman year, we did not have a party.
But most of the other court trips after my freshman year, we'd always have parties, and the blind dates would be arranged and everything.
You got there, somebody had a car.
I think in my outfit, probably one out of every four guys had an automobile, five guys, maybe even less.
But you always managed to get a ride, and it was kind of like the big thing then, of course, were the hometown clubs, because especially if you lived a good ways,
from the campus because that's how you could figure out how you get home.
You stayed in contact with the people going back, maybe Wichita Falls.
Even though, as I say, I hitchhiked home a lot back and forth.
Not that much, but.
Describe hitchhiking to your expert.
Usually wear your uniform because it helped.
I had an old leather suitcase and I had that
that T, which everybody knew it stood for A&M on it.
And you might, from here to Jacksboro, it might take 13 different people.
You never even had any ill feelings or fear or anything about hitchhiking.

You and nowadays of course everybody knows you you got to be afraid of the person picking you up as well as the person you're picking up, but I can remember to the well to this day I might go through Marlin or somewhere and I'll see a Intersection there a country far in the market road and just remember being there Fort Worth for an example if you happen to go that way instead of cutting through a
Meridian, Clifton, Stephenville, Highco, that direction, Middle Wales to get to Jacksonville.

A lot of times that road going on north through Fort Worth, you'd have to get out, and you'd have to walk all the way across Fort Worth, which probably was what we thought was a long ways, but was probably a couple of miles to get to Jacksonville.
to Henderson Street or Jacksboro Highway, as they call it.
Were there kind of special places where you'd hitchhike?
Sure.
Out of Waco, Highway 6, where it used to come in, there was the shed that you'd always gather there.
Out here, just right outside
Eastgate here, Eastgate Lounge with the bus station and all that on down to where University Towers is is where people would go.
And there was kind of a standard rule.
You waited your turn.
You didn't go and get in front of somebody, you know.
And hopefully the cars coming would pick the first guys up.
And so it was like standing in line for a sale.
on the day after Christmas, you know, you just don't go and get in front of those people.
And you might get out of an old pickup into an air-conditioned car, you know.
Did you ever have any negative experience?
About the only negative experience was I was wondering what I was doing when I'm out there still 11 o'clock at night trying to get home.
Nobody ever took a problem?
shot at me or anything, any kind of what you'd call the advances you worry about or being robbed or anything.
Probably the best experience I ever had was a guy picked me up outside of Jacksburg going to Houston.
And when he got up to in front of the campus,
I pointed over there to Dorm 2 because you didn't have the oceanography, meteorology, or any of those buildings.
I said, that's my dorm with the lights.
And I can just remember he says, son, I brought you this for you.
I'm going to take you to your door.
But you didn't think anything about it.
I grew up, we wanted to go swimming in Graham.
We hitchhiked there.
All right, back to academics.
Was the second semester better, your freshman year?
Second semester was a little bit better.
I never was below, the entire time I was in school here, I never was below a C average, but I never did really do anything.
Probably did the best my junior year when I would have had what you call a three-point, a little over a three-point that one semester.
But I was taking 18 hours that semester, too.
But I didn't learn to manage my time probably till my junior year.
Did you ever during that freshman year ever think about dropping out of school?
Only one time.
I guess when I was losing so much weight that before probably about the fifth or sixth week.
And I remember my father only told me two things referenced by going to A&M.
One was he told me to, well, can I wait till the end of the semester, which I did.
The other time at the end of my sophomore year, I was going to drop out of school.

and I joined the Marines and so I quit going to class and I was working as an intramural manager and I would sign up the tennis that spring out on the tennis court and so I would play tennis from five o'clock till sometimes stay there because I was
I was now a junior.
I didn't have to worry about formation.
We might play 7, 8 o'clock at night.
I would just stay over there.
And that's when, at the end of the semester, I told my daddy I was going to join the Marines.
And he said, no, he wished I wouldn't.
And so I kind of turned my act around after that.
It took me, I was still majoring in pre-vet after four semesters, having flunked freshman chemistry twice and English.
And, you know, knowing, but I didn't have any idea I wasn't going to get, but it was, I was in the, I wanted to stay in the company that I was in.
Grades were not, I was still passing.
So, I guess, you know, I just came back my junior year.
I looked around and I said, what, what can I major in?
that was still in the agricultural arena.
And I looked at, in the Department of Ag, Eco, and Rural Sociology, I looked at rural sociology.
And I took a couple of courses over there.
And the professors were truly outstanding.
Dr. Russell.
Describe him.
Dr. Russell, Dr. Dan, the grade point man,
probably one of the most interesting individuals we'll ever meet and when I was involved the other day in helping Dr. Bowen on

getting the ring back here, the Prisoner of War, I mean, keep thinking of that, the Medal of Honor ring, I told him, because he was so enthused about that, I said, you need to go to the library and get out Dr. Russell's scrapbook over there in the old library, Cushing, and read about the project houses that he was involved in.
That is the most amazing piece of, or collection of
articles and letters and things that I've seen on this campus, what the project houses were about and all of that.
But he was a tremendous individual, had had a lot of experience.
going to graduate school, worked as a bartender in Chicago during Al Capone's days.
So he had some good stories.
Been on the board of pardon and parole, I guess, for the state.
And I had Dr. Sperbonik, who was.
Stay with Russia.
OK.
Describe him.
I don't know.
What physically?
Kind of a heavy set, a white haired gentleman, kind of the Santa Claus looking.
He was so interested in students.
I know his.
His wife, they live just a few houses from where my wife grew up here a block off campus.
And her brother was in charge of the recreation department of the city of Dallas.
So he had even got me a job up there one summer, because I thought that might be the area that I want to go.
I didn't do it.
Didn't take the job, but I got offered the job through him.
But he was just a very caring individual.
And I think at that time, we thought he was
rather old.
Like most of us, I thought my first grade teacher was old, but she was still teaching when I graduated from college.
But he was an individual that was pretty easy grading.
I think one of the things that he did for me
which I didn't realize it at the time.

My senior year, there was a two-hour class about Boy Scouts, and at that time I thought I might want to go to work for the Scouts too, and so I had a Scout troop at the Bryan Boys Club, Hispanic young men who, we never had a uniform, but every Monday night we had Scout meeting there, and at that time I had an automobile, so I would take them home after Scout meeting, they would get there by themselves,
and we'd meet for about an hour and a half and I remember
taken them camping out here at some land Dr. Dan had.
But he was a truly, I put him in the same boat as some of the other people that I was involved with, like Mr. Penberthy or Mr.
Gay.
And Professor Russell, what was his style in class?
What was his manner of?
Very, very easygoing.
a nice guy, so nice nobody would take advantage of.

And I think though, I think the rural sociology department was very small, a pretty tight group, and there wasn't any, I think the people that were in that department, majoring in there, it wasn't considered a
department you go, even though the curriculum was not as tough as some of them.
But it was kind of an off-the-wall major, and a lot of the people that were in there, it seemed to me, were from small towns.
And I think that back then, that really made a difference.
Right.
And you started to mention some other folks.
Oh, yeah.
I had Dr. Skrobonek, who was such a tremendous.
And to this day, I've had many, many opportunities to be around him.
Excuse me one second.
